    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>// Which Events the Shopify CAPI Sends</h2>
  <p>
    A complete CAPI implementation sends the following events server-side to ad platforms. Each event includes hashed customer identifiers (email, phone, name) to enable user matching and accurate attribution:
  </p>
  <div class="events-list">
    <div class="event-tag">Purchase</div>
    <div class="event-tag">InitiateCheckout</div>
    <div class="event-tag">AddToCart</div>
    <div class="event-tag">ViewContent</div>
    <div class="event-tag">PageView</div>
    <div class="event-tag">CompleteRegistration</div>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:12px; color:var(--muted); margin-top:0.5rem;">Purchase and InitiateCheckout are the highest-priority events for ad optimisation — these are where browser pixel loss has the most impact on campaign performance.</p>

  <h2>// Deduplication — The Critical Detail</h2>
  <p>
    Running CAPI alongside browser pixels (recommended) requires deduplication. Without it, both the browser pixel and the CAPI will send a Purchase event for the same order — resulting in double-counted conversions in your ad platform reporting. Deduplication works by assigning a shared <code>event_id</code> to both the browser pixel event and the server-side CAPI event. When ad platforms receive two events with the same <code>event_id</code>, they count it as one conversion. CAPI Shield handles deduplication automatically.
  </p>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <div class="label">IMPLEMENTATION NOTE</div>
    <p style="margin:0; font-size:13px;">Meta's Conversions API requires a valid <strong>Access Token</strong> from Meta Business Manager and a <strong>Dataset ID</strong> (formerly Pixel ID). Google Enhanced Conversions requires a Google Tag Manager server-side container or direct integration via Google Ads API. Both are configured once — CAPI Shield handles the technical setup for both platforms.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- FAQ ACCORDION -->
